WATER SCATTER/OPACITY = water-COLUMN optical path = (water DEPTH below the fragment) / NoV (view-angle lengthening), with a SMOOTH Beer exponential and a SHORT e-fold (strong fog, ~8m) so the deep underwater background is fully obscured. THREE traps eliminated in order on one task: (1) Using camera-to-surface VIEW DISTANCE for the optical path is WRONG -- it scales with ALTITUDE, so looking straight down from km up at shallow water reads 100% opaque milk. Use DEPTH, not view distance. (2) The 'windows at an angle' a user reported from depth-keyed opacity came from a HARD threshold (smoothstep) stepping per coarse water-mesh cell -- a SMOOTH exp(-depth/scale) with NO thresholds removes the stepping; depth itself is fine. (3) The white/milky SHEET is the bright-SKY Fresnel REFLECTION, NOT the scatter -- cap reflection weight very low (<=0.08) and TINT the reflected colour toward the deep-blue scatter colour so a full Fresnel reflection is blue not white; never weight reflection UP by depth/scatter (that makes grazing water more reflective = more milk). The grazing 1/NoV term belongs on the SCATTER (deep ray crosses more water -> more blue), correct and wanted. Use a SATURATED deep-blue scatter colour (low red) so accumulated scatter reads as sea, not a pale milk mixed from bright refracted sand. The right decomposition: scatter = depth/NoV geometry; milk = reflection -- fix them separately.